  <h1 id="top">Random Variables, Expectation &amp; Variance</h1>
  <p>The engine room of probability. Every named distribution in Modules 1.4–1.8 is a specific PMF or PDF plugged into this machinery: normalize → compute E[X] → compute Var(X) → apply linear transform rules.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 1: RANDOM VARIABLES ═══ -->
<h2 id="rvs">Random Variables</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  A random variable $X$ maps each outcome of an experiment to a real number. It is <strong>discrete</strong> if it takes countably many values (PMF), or <strong>continuous</strong> if it takes values on an interval (PDF).
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Discrete — PMF</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$p(x) = P(X = x)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Valid: $p(x) \ge 0$ and $\sum p(x) = 1$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Continuous — PDF</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(x) \ge 0, \quad \int_&#123;-\infty&#125;^\infty f(x)\,dx = 1$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$f(x)$ is a density — it can exceed 1. Only areas are probabilities.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-formula-panel">
  <div class="gd-formula-label">CDF (both discrete and continuous)</div>
  <div class="gd-formula">$$F(x) = P(X \le x), \qquad P(a < X \le b) = F(b) - F(a)$$</div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--insight">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">CDF properties (tested verbatim — 2026 Q54)</span>
    Non-decreasing · $F(-\infty)=0$, $F(+\infty)=1$ · right-continuous · for discrete: jumps of size $p(x)$ at each mass point. Median $m$ solves $F(m)=0.5$.
  </div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">GATE Trap — continuous $P(X = x) = 0$</span>
    For a continuous RV, the probability of any single point is exactly 0. Never read a PDF value as a probability. CDF is right-continuous, not left-continuous — exam questions test this directly.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 2: EXPECTATION ═══ -->
<h2 id="expectation">Expectation</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  $E[X]$ is the long-run average — the centre of mass of the distribution.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Discrete E[X]</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[X] = \sum_x x \cdot p(x)$$</div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Continuous E[X]</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[X] = \int_&#123;-\infty&#125;^\infty x \cdot f(x)\,dx$$</div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">LOTUS — E[g(X)]</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[g(X)] = \sum_x g(x)\,p(x)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Weight $g(x)$ by the original distribution. No need to find the distribution of $g(X)$ first.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Linearity (always true)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[aX + b] = aE[X] + b$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X+Y] = E[X]+E[Y]$ even when $X$, $Y$ are dependent.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Jensen — $E[g(X)] \ne g(E[X])$ in general</span>
    Key case: $E[X^2] \ne (E[X])^2$. Always use LOTUS to get $E[X^2]$, then $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2$. Equating them is the #1 variance trap.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ VIZ 1: DRAGGABLE PMF ═══ -->
<h2 id="viz1">Interactive — E[X] as Centre of Mass</h2>

<div class="gd-formula-panel gd-formula-panel--split">
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Definitions</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[X] = \sum_i x_i p_i, \qquad \text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = E[X^2] - \mu^2$$</div>
  </div>
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Current values</div>
    <div class="gd-formula-live" id="exp-live">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="draggable-hint">Drag any bar up or down to change its probability. Probabilities auto-normalise to sum to 1.</div>
<div class="gd-chart" style="position:relative;">
  <div class="gd-chart__title">▲ = E[X] balance point · span bars = ±σ from mean</div>
  <div id="pmf-chart"></div>
</div>

<div class="stat-grid">
  <div class="stat-card">
    <div class="stat-card__label">E[X] = μ</div>
    <div class="stat-card__val" id="ex-val">—</div>
  </div>
  <div class="stat-card">
    <div class="stat-card__label">Var(X) = σ²</div>
    <div class="stat-card__val" id="var-val">—</div>
  </div>
  <div class="stat-card">
    <div class="stat-card__label">Std dev σ</div>
    <div class="stat-card__val" id="sd-val">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 3: VARIANCE ═══ -->
<h2 id="variance">Variance</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Variance measures expected squared deviation from the mean. Standard deviation $\sigma = \sqrt&#123;\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)&#125;$ puts spread in the same units as $X$.
</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel">
  <div class="gd-formula-label">Variance — two equivalent forms</div>
  <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = E[(X - \mu)^2] = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2$$</div>
</div>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Scaling + shift rule</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Var&#125;(aX + b) = a^2 \cdot \text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Shift $b$ does not affect spread. Scale $a$ is squared — sign of $a$ irrelevant.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Sum of independent RVs</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Var&#125;(X + Y) = \text&#123;Var&#125;(X) + \text&#123;Var&#125;(Y)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Only when $X, Y$ independent. Otherwise add $2\,\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)$ — covered in Module 1.6.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--insight">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">$\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) \ge 0$ always — use as sanity check</span>
    Since $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2 \ge 0$, we always have $E[X^2] \ge (E[X])^2$. If your computed variance is negative, recheck $E[X^2]$.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ VIZ 2: LINEAR TRANSFORM ═══ -->
<h2 id="viz2">Interactive — Linear Transform E[aX + b]</h2>
<p style="color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;font-size:0.92rem;">
  Shift (b) moves the whole distribution left/right without changing its spread. Scale (a) stretches or compresses it — variance scales by a², not by a.
</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel gd-formula-panel--split">
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Linear transform rules</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[aX+b] = a\,E[X]+b \qquad \text&#123;Var&#125;(aX+b) = a^2\,\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$$</div>
  </div>
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">With current a, b</div>
    <div class="gd-formula-live" id="transform-live">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-chart">
  <div class="gd-chart__title">Original distribution (blue) vs transformed aX+b (orange)</div>
  <div id="transform-chart"></div>
</div>

<div class="gd-controls">
  <div class="gd-controls__title">Transform parameters</div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">a</span> Scale factor</label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="a-val">2.0</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full"><input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="a-slider" min="-3" max="3" step="0.1" value="2"></div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">b</span> Shift</label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="b-val">3.0</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full"><input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="b-slider" min="-10" max="10" step="0.5" value="3"></div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insights__title">Live transform</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--active" id="ins-transform">—</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn" id="ins-var-warn">—</div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 4: CONDITIONAL EXPECTATION ═══ -->
<h2 id="cond-exp">Conditional Expectation</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Conditioning restricts attention to a sub-population. The <em>law of total expectation</em> (tower property) lets you recover the unconditional mean by averaging over the conditioning variable.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Tower Property</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E\big[\,E[X \mid Y]\,\big] = E[X]$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X \mid Y=y]$ is a number; $E[X \mid Y]$ is a random variable (function of $Y$).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Continuous — conditional density</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(y \mid x) = \frac&#123;f(x,y)&#125;&#123;f_X(x)&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Then $E[Y \mid X=x] = \int y\cdot f(y \mid x)\,dy$.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--insight">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">First-step analysis — template for "expected trials until event"</span>
    Define states, let $E_i$ = expected steps from state $i$. Condition on the first step to write a linear equation for each $E_i$, then solve the system. Full worked case: Example 4 (GATE 2024 Q36).
  </div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">$E[X \mid Y=y]$ (number) vs $E[X \mid Y]$ (random variable)</span>
    Plugging in a specific $y$ gives a fixed number. Leaving $Y$ free gives a function of $Y$ — itself a random variable. GATE 2025 Q11 tests this distinction as a standalone MCQ.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ WORKED EXAMPLES ═══ -->
<h2 id="examples">Worked Examples</h2>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 1 · Discrete PMF — normalize, mean, variance</span>
    <p>$X$ has PMF $p(x) = kx$ for $x = 1, 2, 3, 4$ (and 0 otherwise). Find $k$, $E[X]$, and $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Normalize:</strong> $\sum p(x) = k(1+2+3+4) = 10k = 1 \Rightarrow k = 1/10$.</p>
    <p><strong>$E[X]$:</strong> $\sum x \cdot (x/10) = (1^2+2^2+3^2+4^2)/10 = 30/10 = 3$.</p>
    <p><strong>$E[X^2]$ via LOTUS:</strong> $\sum x^2 \cdot (x/10) = (1^3+2^3+3^3+4^3)/10 = 100/10 = 10$.</p>
    <p><strong>Variance:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2 = 10 - 9 = 1$.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">k = 1/10 · E[X] = 3 · Var(X) = 1</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 2 · Continuous PDF — normalize, probability, mean, variance</span>
    <p>$X$ has PDF $f(x) = kx$ for $0 \le x \le 2$ (and 0 otherwise). Find $k$, $P(X \le 1)$, $E[X]$, $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Normalize:</strong> $\int_0^2 kx\,dx = k[x^2/2]_0^2 = 2k = 1 \Rightarrow k = 1/2$.</p>
    <p><strong>$P(X \le 1)$:</strong> $\int_0^1 (x/2)\,dx = [x^2/4]_0^1 = 1/4$.</p>
    <p><strong>$E[X]$:</strong> $\int_0^2 x \cdot (x/2)\,dx = (1/2)(8/3) = 4/3 \approx 1.333$.</p>
    <p><strong>$E[X^2]$ via LOTUS:</strong> $\int_0^2 x^2 \cdot (x/2)\,dx = (1/2)(16/4) = 2$.</p>
    <p><strong>Variance:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = 2 - (4/3)^2 = 2 - 16/9 = 2/9 \approx 0.222$.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">k = 1/2 · P(X ≤ 1) = 1/4 · E[X] = 4/3 · Var(X) = 2/9</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 3 · GATE 2025 Q39 — reading a probability off a CDF</span>
    <p>$F_X(x) = 0$ for $x \le -1$;&nbsp; $= \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;(x+1)^2$ for $-1 \le x \le 1$;&nbsp; $= 1$ for $x \ge 1$. Find $P(X^2 \le 0.25)$.<br>
    (A) 0.625 &nbsp;&nbsp; (B) 0.25 &nbsp;&nbsp; (C) 0.5 &nbsp;&nbsp; (D) 0.5625</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Event transform first:</strong> $X^2 \le 0.25 \iff \lvert X \rvert \le 0.5 \iff -0.5 \le X \le 0.5$.</p>
    <p><strong>CDF difference:</strong> $P = F(0.5) - F(-0.5)$.</p>
    <p>$F(0.5) = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;(1.5)^2 = 0.5625$,&nbsp; $F(-0.5) = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;(0.5)^2 = 0.0625$.</p>
    <p>$P = 0.5625 - 0.0625 = 0.5$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin-top:6px;">Trap: option (D) 0.5625 = forgetting to subtract $F(-0.5)$. Always use $F(b)-F(a)$ for an interval.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (C) 0.5</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 4 · GATE 2024 Q36 — expected waiting time via first-step analysis</span>
    <p>A fair die is thrown repeatedly. What is the expected number of throws until <strong>two consecutive even numbers</strong> appear?<br>
    (A) 2 &nbsp;&nbsp; (B) 4 &nbsp;&nbsp; (C) 6 &nbsp;&nbsp; (D) 8</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p>$P(\text&#123;even&#125;) = 1/2$. Define states: $S_0$ = no progress, $S_1$ = last throw was even. Let $E_0, E_1$ = expected remaining throws from each state.</p>
    <p><strong>From $S_0$:</strong> throw costs 1. Even (prob 1/2) → go to $S_1$; odd → stay at $S_0$.
    $$E_0 = 1 + \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;E_1 + \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;E_0 \;\Rightarrow\; E_0 = 2 + E_1$$</p>
    <p><strong>From $S_1$:</strong> second even (prob 1/2) → done (0 more); odd → reset to $S_0$.
    $$E_1 = 1 + \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125; \cdot 0 + \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;E_0$$</p>
    <p><strong>Solve:</strong> substitute $E_0 = 2 + E_1$: $E_1 = 1 + \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;(2 + E_1) = 2 + \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;E_1 \Rightarrow E_1 = 4$, so $E_0 = 6$.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (C) 6</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ GATE ANGLE ═══ -->
<div class="gd-gate-box">
  <div class="gd-gate-box__title">GATE DA Angle</div>
  <p><strong>$E[X^2] \ne (E[X])^2$:</strong> always compute $E[X^2]$ via LOTUS, then $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2$. This subtraction step is the most-missed calculation in the entire module.</p>
  <p><strong>$\text&#123;Var&#125;(aX+b) = a^2\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$:</strong> shift $b$ disappears; scale $a$ is squared, sign irrelevant. Answer is immediate — no recomputation needed. Tested almost every year.</p>
  <p><strong>Event transforms:</strong> for $P(X^2 \le c)$, rewrite as $\lvert X \rvert \le \sqrt&#123;c&#125;$, then $F(\sqrt&#123;c&#125;) - F(-\sqrt&#123;c&#125;)$. Forgetting the lower bound is the exact trap in GATE 2025 Q39.</p>
  <p><strong>First-step analysis:</strong> define states, write $E_i$ by conditioning on the first step, solve the linear system. Template: Example 4 (GATE 2024 Q36). Pattern repeats across papers.</p>
  <p><strong>Tower property:</strong> $E\big[E[X \mid Y]\big] = E[X]$. Know the distinction: $E[X \mid Y=y]$ is a number; $E[X \mid Y]$ is a random variable. GATE 2025 Q11 is a standalone MCQ on exactly this point.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ PREV / NEXT ═══ -->
<div class="gd-page-nav">
  <a class="gd-page-nav__item" href="/module1/viz-1-2-bayes.html">
    <span class="gd-page-nav__dir">← Previous</span>
    <span class="gd-page-nav__title">1.2 Bayes' Theorem</span>
  </a>
  <a class="gd-page-nav__item gd-page-nav__item--next" href="/module1/viz-1-4-distributions.html">
    <span class="gd-page-nav__dir">Next →</span>
